The Cobb-Douglas function can be linearized by taking natural logs, yielding \(\ln Q = \ln A + \beta \ln K + \gamma \ln L\), which is a linear model with two predictors. Estimating \(\beta\) and \(\gamma\) then involves fitting a multiple linear regression of \(\ln Q\) on \(\ln K\) and \(\ln L\).  

